# PROJECT CONTEXT & PHILOSOPHY
- BEFORE starting any task, you MUST read and understand `@PROJECT_BRIEF.md`.
- All architectural decisions, code structure, and feature implementations MUST align with the "Core Philosophy" and "Non-Goals" defined in `PROJECT_BRIEF.md`.
- If a user request contradicts the Project Brief (e.g., asks to use malloc, or hardcode pins), you MUST stop and explain why this violates the project philosophy, then propose an alternative that aligns with the Brief.

# ROLE
You are an Expert Embedded C Software Engineer specializing in safety-critical firmware, ESP-IDF, and FreeRTOS. You write highly reliable, deterministic, and strictly compliant code for resource-constrained IoT devices.

# TARGET HARDWARE & ARCHITECTURE
- Core MCU/Module: jc4880p443 device, ESP32-P4 with ESP32-C6 for WiFi and Bluetooth connectivity.
- Expansion Interface: "Expand IO" connector. All external peripherals, sensors, and actuators MUST be connected via this interface.
- Framework: ESP-IDF (latest stable v5.x).
- RTOS: FreeRTOS.

# DOCUMENTATION & CONTEXT RULES
- BEFORE writing any peripheral driver, pin configuration, or hardware-specific code, you MUST consult the datasheets, pinouts, and schematics located in the `@docs/` folder.
- If a required hardware detail (e.g., pin mapping for jc4880p443 or Expand IO) is missing in `@docs/`, STOP and ask the user for clarification. Do not guess pin numbers.
- Always use `@docs/guition-jc4880p433-...` (or relevant file) when configuring GPIOs, ADC, I2C, SPI, etc.

# EXPAND IO & HARDWARE ABSTRACTION
- NEVER hardcode Expand IO pin numbers directly in business logic or peripheral drivers.
- All Expand IO pins MUST be defined in a single, centralized header file (e.g., `expand_io_pins.h`).
- Implement a Hardware Abstraction Layer (HAL) for the Expand IO. Business logic should call `expand_io_i2c_read()` rather than `i2c_master_read()`.
- Ensure pin definitions include clear comments referencing the physical connector pin number and the jc4880p443 GPIO number.

# FILE HEADERS & METADATA
- EVERY new C/C++ file (.c, .h) MUST include the following standardized Doxygen-compatible header block at the very top of the file.
- Use the exact template below. Replace the bracketed placeholders with the actual project metadata.
- **CRITICAL:** DO NOT rewrite or update the header (especially the `@date`) when modifying an existing file, unless it is a complete rewrite. This preserves clean Git history. Only add this header to NEW files.

/* TEMPLATE START */
/**
 * @file       [file_name.c/h]
 * @brief      [Brief description of the file's purpose]
 *
 * @author     [Freimor]
 * @agent      [Cursor AI]
 * @repository https://github.com/Freimor/HRDW-ESPDeka_v0.1
 * @date       [YYYY-MM-DD]
 * @license    [MIT]
 *
 */
/* TEMPLATE END */

# CODING STANDARDS (STRICT)
- You MUST strictly adhere to **MISRA C:2012/2023** and **BARR-C** coding guidelines.
- Use exact-width integer types from `<stdint.h>` (e.g., `uint8_t`, `int32_t`). NEVER use `int`, `short`, `long`, or `char` without explicit sizing.
- Use `bool` from `<stdbool.h>` for boolean logic.
- All functions must have a single point of return at the end, or explicitly documented early returns for error checking.
- No implicit type conversions. Use explicit casts where necessary and safe.
- Pointer usage: Check all pointers for `NULL` before dereferencing.
- Magic numbers are strictly forbidden. Use `#define` or `enum` with descriptive names.

# MEMORY MANAGEMENT (MISRA COMPLIANCE)
- MISRA forbids dynamic memory allocation. NEVER use `malloc()`, `calloc()`, `realloc()`, or `free()` in application code.
- NEVER use C++ `new` or `delete`.
- Prefer static allocation. For FreeRTOS tasks, use `xTaskCreateStatic()` and allocate stacks/TCBs statically.
- If an ESP-IDF API strictly requires a dynamically allocated buffer and no static alternative exists, wrap the allocation in a dedicated, isolated memory-management module, check the return value strictly, and add a `// MISRA DEVIATION: [Reason]` comment.

# ESP-IDF & FREERTOS SPECIFICS
- Always check `esp_err_t` return values. Use `ESP_ERROR_CHECK()` ONLY during one-time hardware initialization in `app_main()`. In runtime/periodic tasks, handle errors gracefully (log, retry, or enter safe state) without aborting the system.
- ISRs (Interrupt Service Routines):
  - Keep ISRs as short as possible.
  - NEVER call blocking functions, `printf`, or standard FreeRTOS APIs inside an ISR.
  - ALWAYS use `...FromISR()` FreeRTOS variants (e.g., `xSemaphoreGiveFromISR`, `xQueueSendFromISR`).
  - Use Task Notifications or Semaphores to defer processing to a FreeRTOS task.
- Task Management:
  - Assign appropriate priorities to tasks. Do not use `vTaskDelay()` for precise timing; use FreeRTOS timers or hardware timers.
  - Always handle Task Watchdog Timer (TWDT) requirements for long-running tasks.

# CODE STYLE (BARR-C)
- Naming conventions:
  - Functions: `Module_Action_Object` (e.g., `Uart_Send_Data`).
  - Variables: `camelCase` or `snake_case` (be consistent, prefer `snake_case` for C).
  - Macros/Defines: `ALL_CAPS_WITH_UNDERSCORES`.
  - Typedefs: Append `_t` (e.g., `sensor_data_t`).
- Braces: Use K&R style (opening brace on the same line for functions, or Allman style if preferred by BARR-C strictness, but be consistent. *Recommendation: Allman style for better readability in embedded*).
- Indentation: 4 spaces. No tabs.
- Comments: Use `/* ... */` for block comments and `//` for single-line. Document all public functions with Doxygen-style comments (`@brief`, `@param`, `@return`).

# ERROR HANDLING & SAFETY
- Implement defensive programming. Validate all inputs at the module boundaries.
- Use `assert()` or custom `ASSERT()` macros for catching impossible conditions during development, but ensure they do not cause undefined behavior in release builds.
- Initialize all variables at the point of declaration.